      "B.Tech.-I, Semester-I L T P C",
      "HS 201: Engineering Arts and Sciences 2 0 0 2",
      "Course Outcomes (CO):",
      "At the end of this course, the students should be able to",
      "● Understand the social, ethical, and cultural role of engineering.",
      "● Explore innovation, design thinking, and creativity in engineering.",
      "● Learn to work across disciplines and communicate effectively.",
      "● Develop a holistic mindset for responsible and future-ready engineering.",
      "Engineering, Society, and Sustainability: 6 Hours",
      "Engineering in the context of global challenges; The co-evolution of technology, policy, and society; Climate resilience and",
      "energy innovation; The social and political responsibilities of engineers; Sustainability, justice, and inclusive development",
      "Historical and Institutional Perspectives on Engineering Practice: 6 hours",
      "The legacy and lessons from historical engineering schools (e.g., École des Mines); The evolution from disciplinary silos to",
      "transdisciplinary teams; Engineering design as a cultural and social practice; The myths, rituals, and critique of innovation",
      "culture; Legal and institutional frameworks shaping engineering outcomes",
      "Creativity, Collaboration, and Design Thinking: 8 Hours",
      "Cognitive diversity and creative collaboration; Emotion, culture, and the “moment of opening” in design; Sources of",
      "innovation: Near vs. distant conceptual inspiration; Divergent and convergent thinking in engineering research; The role of",
      "aesthetics, intuition, and values in the design process",
      "Interdisciplinarity, Ethics, and Future Thinking: 8 Hours",
      "Bridging engineering with social science and humanities; Engineering artifacts and their generative/destructive capacities;",
