      "B.Tech. II Semester-4 L T P C EC 402: Communication Systems 3 0 2 4 Prerequisite Signals & Systems, Probability and Random Variables, Statistical Averages, Transformation of Random Variables, The Central Limit Theorem Unit-1 10 Hours Amplitude Modulation: Amplitude Modulation, Virtues, Limitations, and Modifications of Amplitude Modulation, Quadrature-Carrier Multiplexing, Baseband Representation of Modulated Waves and Band-Pass Filters. Angle Modulation: Basic Definitions, Properties of Angle-Modulated Waves, Relationship between PM and FM waves, Narrow-Band Frequency Modulation, Wide-Band Frequency Modulation, Transmission Bandwidth of FM Waves, Generation of FM waves. Unit-2 16 Hours Pulse Modulation: Sampling Process, Pulse-Amplitude Modulation, Pulse-Position Modulation, Completing the Transition from Analog to Digital (Sampling Process, Quantization Process, and Encoding Process), Pulse Code Modulation, Delta Modulation, Differential Pulse-Code Modulation, Line Codes, Theme Examples. Digital Band-Pass Modulation Techniques: Some Preliminaries, Binary Amplitude-Shift Keying, Phase Shift Keying, Frequency-Shift Keying, Summary of Three Binary Signalling Schemes, Noncoherent Digital Modulation Schemes, M-ary Digital Modulation Schemes, Mapping of Digitally Modulated waveforms onto Constellations of Signal Points, Theme Examples. Unit-3 16 Hours Information and Forward Error Corrections: Uncertainty, Information and Entropy, Source Coding Theorem, Data Compression (Prefix Coding, Huffman Coding), Channel Capacity, Shannon-Hartley Law, Error Control Coding, Linear Block Codes, Hamming Codes. Random Signals and Noise: Random Processes, Stationary Random Process, Mean, and Covariance, Ergodic Process, Spectra of Random Signals, Gaussian Processes, White Noise, Narrowband Noise, Noise in Digital Communication, Bit Error Rate (BER). Reference Books: 1. Simon Haykin and Michael Moher, \"Introduction to Analog and Digital Communication\", John Wiley & Sons, 2nd Edition. 2. Simon Haykin and Michael Moher, \"Communication Systems\", John Wiley & Sons, 5th Edition. 3. Lathi B. P., and Ding Zhi, “Modern Digital & Analog Communication Systems”, Oxford University Press, 4th Edition, 2010. 4. Proakis J., and Salehi M., “Fundamentals of Communication Systems”, PHI/Pearson Education-LPE, 2nd Edition, 2006. 5. Carlson Bruce A., “Communication Systems- An Introduction to Signal and Noise in Electrical Communication”, McGraw-Hill, 5th Edition, 2009. 6. Leon W. Couch, “Digital & Analog Communication Systems”, Pearson Education-LPE, 6th Edition, 2004.",
      "B.Tech. II Semester-4 L T P C EC 403: Engineering Electromagnetics 3 0 0 3 Prerequisite Vector Calculus, Coordinate Systems (Rectangular, Cylindrical, Spherical) Unit-1 8 Hours Basic Laws of Electromagnetics: Review, Divergence & Stoke's Theorem, Gauss Law, Laplace's & Poisson's Equation, Faraday’s Law & Ampere’s work, Law in the differential vector form, Biot Savart's Law. Maxwell's Equations: Introduction, The Equation of Continuity For Time-Varying Fields, Inconsistency of Ampere's Law, Maxwell’s Equation, Condition at a Boundary surface. Unit-2 10 Hours Electromagnetic Wave Theory: Solution for Free-Space conditions, Uniform Plane Waves & Propagation, The Wave Equations for a Conducting Medium, Sinusoidal Time Variations, Conductors and Dielectrics, Polarization, Reflection by a Perfect Conductor Normal & Oblique Incidence, Reflection by a Perfect Dielectric - Normal Incidence & Oblique Incidence, Reflection at The Surface of a Conductive Medium, Poynting Theorem. Unit-3 10 Hours Transmission Line Theory: Wave propagation on a transmission line, The lossless line; Field Analysis of Transmission Lines: Transmission line parameters, The Telegrapher Equations Derived from Field Analysis of a Coaxial Line, Propagation Constant, Impedance, and Power Flow for the Lossless, Coaxial Line; The terminated Lossless transmission line. The Smith Chart: The Combined Impedance–Admittance Smith Chart, The Quarter-Wave Transformer: The Impedance Viewpoint, The Multiple-Reflection Viewpoint; Generator and Load Mismatches: Load Matched to Line, Generator Matched to Loaded Line, Conjugate Matching. Unit-4 14 Hours Waveguides: General Solutions for TEM, TE, and TM Waves: TEM Waves, TE Waves, TM Waves, Attenuation Due to Dielectric Loss; Parallel Plate Waveguide: TEM Modes, TM Modes, TE Modes; Rectangular Waveguide: TE Modes, TM Modes, TEm0 & TE0n Modes of a Partially Loaded Waveguide. Antenna Fundamentals: Radiation Mechanism, Basic Antenna Parameters: Radiation Pattern, Radiation Power Density, Radiation Intensity, Beam Width, Directivity, Antenna Efficiency, Gain, Beam Efficiency, Bandwidth, Polarization, Input Impedance, Antenna Vector Effective Length And Equivalent Areas, Antenna Radiation Efficiency, FRIIS Transmission Equation. Total Contact Time: 42 Hours Reference Books: 1. R. K. Shevgaonkar, “Electromagnetic Waves”, Tata McGraw Hill, 1st Edition, 2006. 2. Jordan E. C. and Balmain K. G., “Electromagnetic Waves and Radiating Systems”, Prentice Hall, Reprint, 2010. 3. David M. Pozar, “Microwave Engineering”, 4th Edition, John Wiley & Sons. 4. Kraus John D., Marhefka Roland J. and Khan Ahmed S., “Antennas and Wave Propagation”, Tata McGraw-Hill, 4th Edition, 2006. 5. William H. Hayt, “Engineering Electromagnetics”, TMH, 8th Edition. David J. Griffiths, “Introduction to Electrodynamics”, Pearson, 4th Edition 6. J. D. Jackson, “Classical Electrodynamics”, Wiley, 3rd Edition 7. Constantine A. Balanis, “Antenna Theory and Applications,”, John Wiley &Sons, 4th Edition, 2021",
      "B.Tech. II Semester-4 L T P C EC 404: Modern Energy Systems 3 0 0 3 Unit-1 10 Hours Introduction to Energy Systems: Overview, Introduction, Relationship between Energy, Population, and Wealth, Pressures Facing World due to Energy Consumption, Units of Measure Used in Energy Systems, Systems Tools for Energy Systems - Conserving Existing Energy Resources versus Shifting to Alternative Resources, Fundamentals of the Systems Approach, Other Tools for Energy Systems. Unit-2 12 Hours Solar Energy System: The Solar Resource, Solar Photovoltaic Technologies, Fundamentals of PV Cell Performance, Design and Operation of Practical PV System, Introduction to Solar Thermal Applications, ACTIVE Solar Heating Systems, Passive Solar Heating Systems. Wind Energy Systems: Overview, Introduction, Using Wind Data to Evaluate a Potential Location, Estimating Output from a Specific Turbine, Turbine Design, Economics of Wind Power. Unit-3 10 Hours Transportation Energy Systems: Overview, Introduction, Vehicle Design Considerations and Alternative, Alternatives to ICEVs: Alternative Fuels and Propulsion Platforms, Well-to-Wheel Analysis as a Means of Comparing Alternatives. Biomass Energy Systems: Introduction, Photosynthesis Process, Usable Forms of Biomass, their Composition and Fuel Properties, Biomass Resources, Biomass Conversion Technologies, Urban Waste to Energy Conversion. Unit-4 10 Hours Hydro-Energy Systems: Introduction, Advantages and Disadvantages of Small Hydro Schemes, Layout of a Micro-Hydro scheme, Water Turbines, Turbine Classification, Characteristics and Selection Generators, Present Status, Nuclear Energy Systems Overview, Introduction, Nuclear Reactions and Nuclear Resources, Reactor Designs: Mature Technologies and Emerging Alternatives, Nuclear Energy and Society: Environmental, Political, and Security Issues. Total Contact Time: 42 Hours Reference Books: 1. R\"Energy Systems Engineering: Evaluation and Implementation\" by Francis Vanek & Louis Albright McH Publication. 2. “Modern Power System Analysis” by D P Kothari, I J Nagaraj & R K Saket. 3. “Non-conventional Energy Resources”, B. H. Khan, Tata McGraw Hill 4. \"Fundamentals of Renewable Energy Systems\" by D. Mukherjee & S. Chakrabarti 5. \"Renewable Energy: Power for a Sustainable Future\" – Godfrey Boyle"
